DataSet Intro

Reading and comprehending the dataset. The data is fairly clean and organized, so I just had to change a few things for simplification. There is a lot of data present, some categorical and some numerical, and the data types make sense for the type of data being looked into. Having all these variables should make it easier to create a prediction model for diabetes. (At least that's what I would expected at this point)

In[45]:
#Creating/adding age groups column
age_groups = [0, 17, 29, 45, 60, 200]
age_labels = ["Child/Teen", "Young Adult", "Adult", "Middle Aged", "Senior"]
df["Age_Group"] = pd.cut(df["Age"], bins=age_groups, labels=age_labels, right=True)

#Flagging for high blood pressure. (Based off typical ranges). Giving it a numerical tag (1=Flagged, 0= Not flagged)
df["High_BP_Flag"] = np.where((df["Blood_Pressure_Systolic"] >= 130) | 
    (df["Blood_Pressure_Diastolic"] >= 80), 1, 0)

Required Visuals

The next couple cells are the visuals required. They yield good info, but it takes some thinking to learn why. At the same time some of the info that comes from it is not very informative, such as the correlation heatmap below. The common trend in this area helps show why it is so hard to predict diabetes. Though there are so many different factors at play, every mode of visualization fails to show clear influence. Many variables express similar correlation and it makes is seem as if lifestyle and even some genetic factors do nothing to predict diabetes reliably.

In[]:

Extra visuals to intensely analyze BMI.

I spent a lot of time studying BMI in the dataset due to its known influence on Diabetes risk. Violin plots were the best method of visualization for these correlations because they also show shape through density, making it easier to see what bins differ a bit. A common trend in this section is that the different factorrs tend to differ only slightly, but that is still important to note as it sheds light on typical expectations. For example, alcohol consumption's expected influence on BMI does not seem to be as strong as some would expect. These visualizations would then help to deter negative stigmas or bad conclusions.

Conclusion

This dataset being so vast and thorough help to show why it is hard to predict diabetes or interpret risk factors today. Even with the differennt tupes of data, different contexts that they factor into (genetic vs lifestyle, etc), nothing seems to be a clear indicator of risk. As medical technology continues to improve, the future could hold more effective screening for diabetes risk, and this would help target prevention over treatment.
